name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gamaches","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Normand, Adrien, Lucien, Marcel, Aime, Andre, Camille, Fernand, Pierre, Raoul, Aldege.","French: habitational name from (La) Gamache or Gamaches, the name of several places in various parts of France, e.g. in Somme, possibly named from the Celtic elements <i>cam</i> ‘bent, winding’ + <i>apia</i> ‘water’.","History: Nicolas Gamache from Saint-Illiers-la-Ville in Yvelines, France, married Élisabeth-Ursule Cloutier in Château-Richer, QC, in 1676."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Arthus","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin.  King Arthur  was a British king of the 5th or 6th century, about whom virtually no historical facts are known. He ruled in Britain after the collapse of the Roman Empire and before the coming of the Germanic tribes, and a vast body of legends grew up around him in the literatures of medieval Western Europe. His name is first found in the Latinized form <i>Artorius</i>; it is of obscure etymology. The spelling with <i>-th-</i> was popular among the gentry families of West Yorkshire in the late 1400s, even before  Henry VII , who may have hoped to capitalize on the legend, gave the name to his son. It remained in regular use in some areas and its popularity exploded in the early 19th century, largely as a result of the fame of  Arthur Wellesley  (  1769–1852 ), Duke of Wellington, the victor at the Battle of Waterloo and subsequently prime minister. Further influences were  Tennyson's  Idylls of the King (  1859–85 ), and the widespread Victorian interest, especially among the Pre-Raphaelites, in things medieval in general and in Arthurian legend in particular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Arthus de Gamaches was born in 1084, in Gamaches, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, his father, Gaucher de Gamaches, was 33 and his mother, Mahaut d'Aumale, was 21. He married Aelixe De Foucarmont in 1119. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1084–":"1084–Surnud","1075–1135":"1075–1135","1079–1132":"1079–1132","1084–Male":"1084–Surnud","1098–1153":"1098–1153","1105–1149":"1105–1149","1121–1184":"1121–1184","1139–1176":"1139–1176","1141–1177":"1141–1177","1051–1116":"1051–1116","1063–1119":"1063–1119","1121":"1121","1176":"1176","1132":"1132","1153":"1153","1098":"1098","1141":"1141","1075":"1075","1063":"1063","1184":"1184","1084":"1084","1051":"1051","1139":"1139","1116":"1116","1149":"1149","1105":"1105","1135":"1135","1079":"1079","1078":"1078","1177":"1177","1119":"1119","Gamaches, Somme, Picardie, France":"Gamaches, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Gamaches, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Gamaches, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1084–":"1084–Kuollut","1075–1135":"1075–1135","1079–1132":"1079–1132","1084–Male":"1084–Kuollut","1098–1153":"1098–1153","1105–1149":"1105–1149","1121–1184":"1121–1184","1139–1176":"1139–1176","1141–1177":"1141–1177","1051–1116":"1051–1116","1063–1119":"1063–1119","1121":"1121","1176":"1176","1132":"1132","1153":"1153","1098":"1098","1141":"1141","1075":"1075","1063":"1063","1184":"